events.description: Otho seizes power in Rome, proclaiming himself Emperor of Rome, beginning a reign of only three months.

events.html: • 1582 – Truce of Yam-Zapolsky: Russia cedes Livonia to the Polish–Lithuanian Commonwealth.[4]

events.description: The British Museum opens to the public.
events.html: • 1759 – The British Museum opens to the public.[5]

events.description: American Revolutionary War: New Connecticut (present-day Vermont) declares its independence.
events.html: • 1777 – American Revolutionary War: New Connecticut (present-day Vermont) declares its independence.[6]

events.description: Superintendent of Finance Robert Morris addresses the U.S. Congress to recommend establishment of a national mint and decimal coinage.
events.html: • 1782 – Superintendent of Finance Robert Morris addresses the U.S. Congress to recommend establishment of a national mint and decimal coinage.[7]

events.description: War of 1812: American frigate USS President, commanded by Commodore Stephen Decatur, is captured by a squadron of four British frigates.
events.html: • 1815 – War of 1812: American frigate USS President, commanded by Commodore Stephen Decatur, is captured by a squadron of four British frigates.[8]

events.description: A paper by David Brewster is read to the Royal Society, belatedly announcing his discovery of what we now call the biaxial class of doubly-refracting crystals. On the same day, Augustin-Jean Fresnel signs a "supplement" (submitted four days later) on reflection of polarized light.
events.html: • 1818 – A paper by David Brewster is read to the Royal Society, belatedly announcing his discovery of what we now call the biaxial class of doubly-refracting crystals.[9] On the same day, Augustin-Jean Fresnel signs a "supplement" (submitted four days later) on reflection of polarized light.

events.description: Greek War of Independence: Demetrios Ypsilantis is elected president of the legislative assembly.
events.html: • 1822 – Greek War of Independence: Demetrios Ypsilantis is elected president of the legislative assembly.

events.description: American Civil War: Fort Fisher in North Carolina falls to the Union, thus cutting off the last major seaport of the Confederacy.
events.html: • 1865 – American Civil War: Fort Fisher in North Carolina falls to the Union, thus cutting off the last major seaport of the Confederacy.[10]

events.description: Forty people die when ice covering the boating lake at Regent's Park, London, collapses.
events.html: • 1867 – Forty people die when ice covering the boating lake at Regent's Park, London, collapses.[11]

events.description: A political cartoon for the first time symbolizes the Democratic Party with a donkey ("A Live Jackass Kicking a Dead Lion" by Thomas Nast for Harper's Weekly).
events.html: • 1870 – A political cartoon for the first time symbolizes the Democratic Party with a donkey ("A Live Jackass Kicking a Dead Lion" by Thomas Nast for Harper's Weekly).

events.description: The first newspaper in Afrikaans, Die Afrikaanse Patriot, is published in Paarl.
events.html: • 1876 – The first newspaper in Afrikaans, Die Afrikaanse Patriot, is published in Paarl.

events.description: The Coca-Cola Company, then known as the Pemberton Medicine Company, is incorporated in Atlanta.
events.html: • 1889 – The Coca-Cola Company, then known as the Pemberton Medicine Company, is incorporated in Atlanta.

events.description: James Naismith publishes the rules of basketball.
events.html: • 1892 – James Naismith publishes the rules of basketball.[12]

events.description: The Alpha Kappa Alpha sorority becomes the first Greek-letter organization founded and established by African American college women.
events.html: • 1908 – The Alpha Kappa Alpha sorority becomes the first Greek-letter organization founded and established by African American college women.

entities.name: Fraternities and sororities in North America

events.description: Construction ends on the Buffalo Bill Dam in Wyoming, United States, which was the highest dam in the world at the time, at 99 m (325 ft).
events.html: • 1910 – Construction ends on the Buffalo Bill Dam in Wyoming, United States, which was the highest dam in the world at the time, at 99 m (325 ft).

events.description: Palestinian Arabic-language Falastin newspaper founded.
events.html: • 1911 – Palestinian Arabic-language Falastin newspaper founded.[13]

events.description: Rosa Luxemburg and Karl Liebknecht, two of the most prominent communists in Germany, are clubbed and then shot to death by members of the Freikorps at the end of the Spartacist uprising.
events.html: • 1919 – Rosa Luxemburg and Karl Liebknecht, two of the most prominent communists in Germany, are clubbed and then shot to death by members of the Freikorps at the end of the Spartacist uprising.[14]

events.description: Great Molasses Flood: A wave of molasses released from an exploding storage tank sweeps through Boston, Massachusetts, killing 21 and injuring 150.
events.html: • 1919 – Great Molasses Flood: A wave of molasses released from an exploding storage tank sweeps through Boston, Massachusetts, killing 21 and injuring 150.

events.description: The 8.0 Mw  Nepal–Bihar earthquake strikes Nepal and Bihar with a maximum Mercalli intensity of XI (Extreme), killing an estimated 6,000–10,700 people.
events.html: • 1934 – The 8.0 Mw  Nepal–Bihar earthquake strikes Nepal and Bihar with a maximum Mercalli intensity of XI (Extreme), killing an estimated 6,000–10,700 people.

events.description: The first building to be completely covered in glass, built for the Owens-Illinois Glass Company, is completed in Toledo, Ohio.
events.html: • 1936 – The first building to be completely covered in glass, built for the Owens-Illinois Glass Company, is completed in Toledo, Ohio.

events.description: Spanish Civil War: Nationalists and Republicans both withdraw after suffering heavy losses, ending the Second Battle of the Corunna Road.

events.description: World War II: The Soviet counter-offensive at Voronezh begins.
events.html: • 1943 – World War II: The Soviet counter-offensive at Voronezh begins.

events.description: The Pentagon is dedicated in Arlington County, Virginia.
events.html: • 1943 – The Pentagon is dedicated in Arlington County, Virginia.

events.description: The Black Dahlia murder: The dismembered corpse of Elizabeth Short was found in Los Angeles.
events.html: • 1947 – The Black Dahlia murder: The dismembered corpse of Elizabeth Short was found in Los Angeles.

events.description: Chinese Civil War: The Communist forces take over Tianjin from the Nationalist government.
events.html: • 1949 – Chinese Civil War: The Communist forces take over Tianjin from the Nationalist government.

events.description: The Derveni papyrus, Europe's oldest surviving manuscript dating to 340 BC, is found in northern Greece.
events.html: • 1962 – The Derveni papyrus, Europe's oldest surviving manuscript dating to 340 BC, is found in northern Greece.

events.description: Netherlands New Guinea Conflict: Indonesian Navy fast patrol boat RI Macan Tutul commanded by Commodore Yos Sudarso sunk in Arafura Sea by the Dutch Navy.
events.html: • 1962 – Netherlands New Guinea Conflict: Indonesian Navy fast patrol boat RI Macan Tutul commanded by Commodore Yos Sudarso sunk in Arafura Sea by the Dutch Navy.

events.description: The First Nigerian Republic, led by Abubakar Tafawa Balewa is overthrown in a military coup d'état.
events.html: • 1966 – The First Nigerian Republic, led by Abubakar Tafawa Balewa is overthrown in a military coup d'état.

events.description: The first Super Bowl is played in Los Angeles. The Green Bay Packers defeat the Kansas City Chiefs 35–10.
events.html: • 1967 – The first Super Bowl is played in Los Angeles. The Green Bay Packers defeat the Kansas City Chiefs 35–10.

events.description: The Soviet Union launches Soyuz 5.
events.html: • 1969 – The Soviet Union launches Soyuz 5.

events.description: Nigerian Civil War: Biafran rebels surrender following an unsuccessful 32-month fight for independence from Nigeria.
events.html: • 1970 – Nigerian Civil War: Biafran rebels surrender following an unsuccessful 32-month fight for independence from Nigeria.

events.description: Muammar Gaddafi is proclaimed premier of Libya.
events.html: • 1970 – Muammar Gaddafi is proclaimed premier of Libya.

events.html: • 1973 – Vietnam War: Citing progress in peace negotiations, President Richard Nixon announces the suspension of offensive action in North Vietnam.

events.html: • 1981 – Pope John Paul II receives a delegation from the Polish trade union Solidarity at the Vatican led by Lech Wałęsa.

events.description: The United Nations deadline for the withdrawal of Iraqi forces from occupied Kuwait expires, preparing the way for the start of Operation Desert Storm.
events.html: • 1991 – The United Nations deadline for the withdrawal of Iraqi forces from occupied Kuwait expires, preparing the way for the start of Operation Desert Storm.

events.description: Elizabeth II, in her capacity as Queen of Australia, signs letters patent allowing Australia to become the first Commonwealth realm to institute its own Victoria Cross in its honours system.

events.html: • 2005 – ESA's SMART-1 lunar orbiter discovers elements such as calcium, aluminum, silicon, iron, and other surface elements on the Moon.

events.description: US Airways Flight 1549 ditches safely in the Hudson River after the plane collides with birds less than two minutes after take-off. This becomes known as "The Miracle on the Hudson" as all 155 people on board were rescued.
